<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Burundi </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Appointment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA0802103794 Kigali Radiodiffusion Nationale de la 
Republique Rwandaise in French 1800 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA0802103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kigali Radiodiffusion Nationale de la 
Republique Rwandaise </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Following his inauguration last week, the new 
president of Burundi, Cyprien Ntaryamira, has just appointed his 
prime minister. He is Anatole Kanyenkiko, former minister of 
public works and equipment in the government of President 
Ndadaye who was assassinated last October. Kanyenkiko, who is 
married and father of three children, comes from the Tutsi 
ethnic group and is a member of the main opposition party, Unity 
and National Progress Party [Uprona]. He hails from Ngozi 
Province, northern Burundi. Before becoming minister of public 
works and equipment he was mayor of Bujumbura. Mr. Kanyenkiko 
replaces Mrs. Sylvie Kinigi, also a member of Uprona. However, 
it was not an easy task to make the appointment. Here is 
Celcius Nsengiyunva, reporting from Bujumbura: 
  [Begin recording] [words indistinct] lasted 48 hours and 
finally at 1300, Radio Burundi announced the appointment of 
Anatole Kanyenkiko as the new prime minister. The choice of Mr. 
Kanyenkiko was not an easy one. The opposition did not make 
things easy for President Cyprien Ntaryamira. In the beginning, 
it was agreed that the president of the Republic would choose 
the prime minister after consultation with all political 
organizations and that the prime minister would come from the 
opposition party in parliament, that is Uprona, the former 
single ruling party. 
  While in the government of Sylvie Kinigi, Anatole Kanyenkiko 
consistently stressed the fact that he was from Uprona party but 
after realizing that the new president was going to choose Mr. 
Kanyenkiko, the opposition [word indistinct] that Kanyenkiko had 
worked with the party in power and claimed that there had been a 
violation of the agreements and that there was a need to 
renegotiate terms. Once again, politicians met this morning at 
a meeting chaired by Bishop Bududira and with the UN envoy, the 
Mauritanian Ahmedou Ould Abdallah, as an observer. 
  Anatole Kanyenkiko replaces Sylvie Kinigi and must form a 
government as soon as possible in which the opposition will take 
up 40 percent of seats while the ruling Front for Democracy in 
Burundi and its supporters will take up 60 percent. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

