<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Ghana </F>
<H3> <TI>   Renewed Fighting in Bimbila Reported 4 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0402190094 Accra Ghana Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in English 1300 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0402190094 </F>
<F P=104>  Accra Ghana Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Fighting has again broken out between the Komkombas 
and Nanumbas in the Bimbila District of the Northern Region. A 
number of villages in the district have either been burned down 
or deserted. Scores of women and children were seen fleeing to 
Yendi, while men armed themselves and took cover in the bush. 
Students and staff of the EP [Evangelic Presbyterian] Training 
College, as well as workers of the Centralized Government 
Department in the town, have taken refuge at the police station, 
where there are Army and police detachments. 
  The Bimbila District secretary, Mr. Ismael A.D. Adams, has 
briefed the Northern Regional minister, Lieutenant Colonel 
Abdulai Ibrahim, and members of the Regional Security Committee 
who had gone to the area. Mr. Adams told them that reports 
indicate the fighting followed a misunderstanding between a 
Komkomba man and a Nanumba man over the sale of a guinea fowl at 
Napayili market. According to him, the owner of the guinea fowl 
was alleged to have refused the price offered him by the 
Komkomba man and sold it to the Nanumba, and this infuriated the 
Komkomba man who went to the Nanumba man's farm the next day and 
shot two persons. Mr. Adams disclosed that one policeman was 
killed and three others were seriously injured when they 
attempted to evacuate their colleagues from Wulinsi police 
station. He said the situation is purely a Nanumba-Komkomba 
conflict and has nothing to do with the recent attack on Bimbila 
police station. 
  Addressing students of the EP Training College and displaced 
people at Bimbila police station, the regional minister said the 
necessary steps would be taken to solve their problems. He gave 
the assurance that transport would be made available to evacuate 
them from the town as early as possible. The first deputy 
speaker of parliament and MP for Bimbila, Dr. Mohamed Ibn 
Chambas, said the government's attention would be drawn to the 
situation to deal with it promptly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-25086 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr026_e_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-026 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Ghana </F>
<H3> <TI>   Committee Assures Residents of Security in Tamale </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0702211094 Accra Ghana Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in English 1800 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0702211094 </F>
<F P=104>  Accra Ghana Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The northern regional security committee has assured 
residents of Tamale that the military and the police are in 
control of the general security in the area and they can 
therefore go about their normal duties without fear. In a 
statement issued at Tamale, the committee requested the public 
to cooperate and warned that any person found involved in 
criminal activities would be severely dealt with. 
  The assurance came in the wake of fears generated by the 
general state of insecurity as a result of mob attacks on 
certain sections of the community since last week. The military 
and police have been deployed at strategic areas in the 
municipality to curb further acts of violence. Some 
reinforcements have also been dispatched to the East Gonja and 
Yendi Districts where fighting is reported to be still going on 
despite the call for cease-fire by the northern sector brigade 
commander of the Ghana Armed Forces. 
  According to people fleeing the fighting from Salaga, the 
casualty rate is high. In another development, Dagbon leaders 
in Tamale have formed a task force to help stop the burning and 
looting of property by irate mobs. 
  Meanwhile, a GHANA NEWS AGENCY report said that the state of 
insecurity had resulted in many people, mainly in the public 
service, leaving the municipality. Already all first and second 
cycle schools in the municipality have closed down following 
threats of mob attack. The National Mobilization Program [NMP] 
and the Red Cross Society in Tamale have, meanwhile, registered 
over 2,000 refugees who have fled the ethnic fighting in parts 
of the region. The refugees are mainly students, national 
service personnel, and displaced people, including women and 
children. The report said that about 600 of the refugees are 
camped at the Nyohene Vocational Center and are fed by the local 
community because the NMP and the Red Cross have nothing in 
stock. It said the rest of the refugees, who feel their lives 
are endangered in Tamale, are being kept in a military camp. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

