<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Chairman of Campaign for Democracy Reelected </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0702145594 Paris AFP in English 1058 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0702145594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lagos, 7 Feb (AFP) -- Beko Ransome-Kuti has been 
re-elected national chairman of Nigeria's pro-democracy Campaign 
for Democracy (CD) umbrella group despite criticism from within 
the leadership, participants in the election said Monday. 
Ransome-Kuti was reelected at a convention on Sunday in Ibadan, 
some 140 kilometres (85 miles) north of Lagos. 
  A group within the CD, led by Chima Ubani, the former CD 
secretary-general, last month accused Dr. Ransome-Kuti of 
"collaborating" with the regime of military ruler General Sani 
Abacha, thereby "compromising" the association. Ransome-Kuti 
has denied the charges. 
  An attempt by the dissenters to pass a vote of no confidence 
in Ransome-Kuti's leadership was defeated by majority of 
participants, sparking a walkout by a number of prominent 
opponents of Ransome-Kuti before the leadership vote, conference 
sources said. Some activists said they would not rule out the 
formation of another human rights group by the opponents of 
Ransome-Kuti's leadership. 

</TEXT>

