<F P=101> Togo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vote Counting Described as Slow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0702220094 Lome Radio Lome in French 1900 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0702220094 </F>
<F P=104>  Lome Radio Lome </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The counting of votes of yesterday's legislative 
elections continues under the supervision of the National 
Electoral Commission [CEN], which made public the first 
provisional results this afternoon. According to these first 
results from 11 constituencies, the Togolese People's Rally is 
leading with six seats, followed closely by the Action Committee 
for Renewal and the Togolese Union for Democracy, which will go 
to the second round of elections in several constituencies. 
[passage omitted] 
  According to the electoral code, the complete results of the 
first round of elections must be communicated to the Supreme 
Court by the evening of 9 February so that they can be 
announced. In an evening radio and television program on the 
elections at the Palais des Congres yesterday, CEN Chairman Kue 
Sipohon Gaba admitted the slowness with which the votes are 
being counted. This slowness is due to lack of sufficient means 
to count the votes. According to the general opinion, voting 
took place in satisfactory conditions. Opposition candidates 
and those from the presidential group unanimously admitted this, 
although they pointed out certain shortcomings in the 
organization. 

</TEXT>

