<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Reported at Standstill; Beye, UNITA Team Absent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0702210494 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0702210494 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Pedro Manuel in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] Good evening. There has been no progress at the 
negotiations this afternoon. The mediators and observers met 
with Jorge Valentim, but it produced nothing. It has been 
reported that, so far, UNITA has not reacted to the document 
issued by the mediators and observers entitled General 
Principles on National Reconciliation. Most of UNITA's 
negotiating team is still in Cote d'Ivoire. Only Jorge Valentim 
is in Lusaka. UN Special Representative Blondin Beye is also in 
Cote d'Ivoire and might return on 9 February. 
  This morning the government team met with the mediators and 
observers. According to a source, the meeting reviewed the 
document issued by the mediators and observers in what could be 
described as the government's first reaction. The source says 
that, in general, the government agrees with the views of the 
mediators and observers and has not proposed major changes to 
the document. 
  A number of questions still need to be addressed -- namely, 
when will the UNITA negotiating team return and what will the 
working agenda in Lusaka be tomorrow? Analysts say it is 
unlikely that the talks will be productive while Beye and 
UNITA's negotiating team are absent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

