<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Army Chief Confident About Peace Process </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0802060894 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
1030 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0802060894 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] General Lelio Goncalves, commander of the UN forces 
in Mozambique, says the Mozambican peace process is heading in 
the right direction. Speaking to the Portuguese news agency, 
LUSA, Goncalves said: The two sides are cooperating and trying 
to ensure the continuity of the process. On 13 February, Gen. 
Goncalves, a Brazilian, ends his 12-month contract with the 
United Nations. He noted that he would only request an 
extension of his mandate if there were a crisis in the 
Mozambican peace process. He said the Mozambican process 
differs a great deal from the Angolan. Goncalves said 
Mozambicans are anxious about peace, the former warring factions 
no longer receive foreign assistance, UN troops are in place, 
and the Mozambique National Resistance is not the National Union 
for the Total Independence of Angola. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

