<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Suggests Foreign Peacekeeping Force </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0702140394 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1141 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0702140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Umtata Feb 7 SAPA--South Africa needed to send an 
SOS to its international allies and arrange an overseas force to 
keep the peace in the country, Maj-Gen Bantu Holomisa, 
Transkei's military ruler, said on Monday [7 February]. 
  Reacting to reported remarks by the National Peacekeeping 
Force [NPKF] commanding officer, Brig Gabriel Ramushwana, that 
the NPKF would not be ready for deployment before and during the 
April general elections, Gen Holomisa said: "South African 
political leaders have no other option but to approach African, 
Asian or Western powers for the assembling of a force to keep 
peace in South Africa or approach the United Nations Security 
Council for the deployment of a UN peace keeping force in the 
country while we are still training and sorting out the current 
problems of the National Peacekeeping Force." 
  He added: "We need to send an SOS call to our friends 
outside South Africa. If we need their capital for investment 
and related assistance, I see no reason why we cannot have 
confidence in them when it comes to security matters. What is 
needed is to agree on the rules and regulations as to how they 
will be involved. The Namibian and Zimbabwean transitional 
arrangements can be used as a model." 
  The general added it was clear the South African Government 
had no interest in seeing the NPKF take off. A total of 10,000 
soliders for the force was the target "but the RSA [Republic of 
South Africa] government saw to it that a mere 3,700 were being 
trained for the purpose. This low number cannot even cordon off 
Soweto when violence flares up." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

