<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Business Confidence Said `Cautiously' Improving </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0702152994 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1334 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0702152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg Feb 7 SAPA -- The country's business 
mood improved cautiously in the December 1993 - January 1994 
period as economic fundamentals continued to improve, the SA 
[South African] Chamber of Business [SACOB] said Monday in 
Johannesburg. SACOB's business confidence index [BCI] improved 
by one percentage point to 104.9 from 103.9 in November last 
year. 
  Releasing the data, chief economist Ben van Rensburg however 
warned that political electioneering before the polls in April 
could result in uncertainty over economic policy and thus harm 
confidence. Electioneering had not helped to bring any clarity 
to economic policy and would increase uncertainty as political 
campaigns intensified. Reconciling populist strategies aimed at 
winning votes with realistic policies which would promote 
business confidence was difficult for many of the political 
players. 
  Dr Van Rensburg said a key measure of this type of 
uncertainty was the capital account which experienced outflows 
of about R[rand]15-billion last year. The index was higher over 
the last two months as a result of an improvement in seven of 
the 13 sub-indices which make up the BCI. 

  -  Stock market prices continued to reach new highs, 
  -  The value of building plans passed climbed markedly, 
  -  Real retail sales were higher on a monthly seasonally 
adjusted 
basis, 
  -  Short-term interest rates edged lower, and 
  -  The gold price firmed on international markets. 

    Negative influences on the BCI included: 

  -  The number of new passenger vehicles sold eased, 
  -  The volume of merchandise imports were lower, 
  -  The exchange rate of the commercial rand against the US 
dollar 
worsened, and 
  -  The official inflation rate increased slightly. 

    Although the economy was definitely in the recovery stage, 
Dr 
Van Rensburg stressed it was vital to achieve a political 
inclusive settlement. This would bolster business and consumer 
confidence leading to an easing in capital outflows as well as 
underpinning the economy. 
  SACOB has forecast a growth rate of between two and 2.5 per 
cent this year following on the economy's contraction over the 
last four years. 

</TEXT>

