<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Status of Lusaka Peace Talks Remains Uncertain </TI></H3>
<H4>   Government, Mediators Discuss Mandate </H4>
<F P=102> MB0802202494 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0802202494 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from Lusaka by correspondent Pedro Manuel] </F>
  [Text] Good evening. The talks are virtually at a 
standstill while the main body of the National Union for the 
Total Independence of Angola [UNITA] negotiating team is awaited. 
  Meanwhile, the mediators and the government delegation are 
busy with something else. There are reports that the government 
team has already reacted to the proposal from the mediators and 
observers on the question of national reconciliation and the 
UNAVEM [UN Angola Verification Mission] mandate. Analysts 
believe the mediators today dealt with the government 
delegation's views on UNAVEM. In the case of national 
reconciliation the government team introduced no major changes, 
though the same cannot be said of the UNAVEM mandate. The 
government has proposed changes because, according to a source, 
it is necessary for the government and the United Nations to 
define juridical aspects so that the government's legal rights 
are upheld. 
  Right now, the talks are dealing with national 
reconciliation 
and the UNAVEM mandate. The talks will only get off the ground 
when the main body of the UNITA delegation returns to Lusaka, 
probably tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

