<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Status of Lusaka Peace Talks Remains Uncertain </TI></H3>
<H4>   UNITA Links Talks to Inquiry Team </H4>
<F P=102> MB0902071694 London BBC World Service in Portuguese 2030 GMT 
8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0902071694 </F>
<F P=104>  London BBC World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "London Last Minute" program] </F>
  [Excerpt] The Lusaka peace talks have taken a breather. At 
a time when national reconciliation is being discussed, the 
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola [UNITA] is 
linking the resumption of the peace talks to an inquiry team 
being sent to Cuito and Huambo to establish who was responsible 
for the resumption of hostilities. At least, that was what 
UNITA Information Secretary Jorge Valentim, spokesman for the 
UNITA team to Lusaka, told the BBC yesterday. 
  [Begin Valentim recording] Our stance is quite clear: We are 
prepared to continue the talks. The UNITA team will stay on in 
Luanda, and it will continue to negotiate with the observers, 
the mediators, and the government's delegation. However, to 
save peace in Angola, we have asked that an inquiry team be set 
up and sent to Bie and Huambo to establish the identity of and 
condemn the aggressor so that peace can be saved in Angola. [end 
recording] 
  Meanwhile, reports reaching us from Luanda are less than 
encouraging. It appears that the government is also hardening 
its stance. In fact, yesterday the Angolan authorities said 
they will not give in to what they described as absurd proposals 
by UNITA. Analysts see this as an indication that the government 
wishes to make no national reconciliation package concessions. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

