<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Status of Lusaka Peace Talks Remains Uncertain </TI></H3>
<H4>   UNITA, Government Trade Accusations </H4>
<F P=102> LD0902100194 Lisbon Radio Renascenca in Portuguese to Europe 
0900 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0902100194 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon Radio Renascenca </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Angola, both UNITA and the government are 
questioning the validity of the Lusaka talks. Rui Oliveira, the 
UNITA representative in Lisbon, has said that the government has 
returned to a strategy of war, and he cites Luanda's armament 
effort as an example. 
  [Begin Oliveira recording] It is the MPLA that is practicing 
a strategy of war. It is buying war materiel from Brazil, 
Russia, and Spain; buying materiel in North Korea. Portugal is 
also involved. As we all know, as it is generally known, 
Portugal is giving the MPLA, the Luanda government military aid. 
[end recording] 
  [Announcer] That was Rui Oliveira of UNITA in Lisbon, the 
spokesman for the accusations that do not even spare Portugal. 
The Angolan Government says it is only defending itself. 
  [Begin David Mendes, Angolan secretary of state for the 
environment, recording] UNITA is not passive, it is using force. 
And [words indistinct] control the use of force, then we also 
defend ourselves with force. The government's purchase of war 
materiel was not part of its plan. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] That was David Mendes, Angolan secretary of 
state 
for the environment, who is currently in Lisbon. In Angola the 
military conflict is being intensified. There are reports of 
air raids on Huambo. Both the government and UNITA claim to 
control 85 percent of Cuito. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

