<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mali </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Affirms Commitment To Pursue Dialogue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0902104194 Bamako Radiodiffusion-Television du Mali Radio 
in French 0700 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0902104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bamako Radiodiffusion-Television du Mali Radio 
in French 0700 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Communique issued by Prime Minister Ibrahim Boubacar Keita </F>
in Bamako; date not given; read by Bakary Koniba Traore, 
minister of equipment and transportation and government 
spokesman--recorded] 
  [Text] In view of the current political and social 
situation and the many disturbances that have affected our 
capital for some time now, I feel the need to make certain 
clarifications in my capacity as head of government. More than 
ever before, I would like to reaffirm my unflinching 
determination, as well as the determination of the government 
that I have the honor to head, to primarily resort to dialogue 
with all our partners in order to find solutions to the problems 
of our nation. We have taken cognizance of the defection of a 
few cabinet members at this time of a serious crisis that is 
affecting our country and the entire West African subregion. We 
believe that all democrats and patriots--all true sons of 
Mali--wherever they may be, will understand the need to join 
hands in our efforts to overcome the current predicaments and to 
avert threats against the democratic process and the very future 
of our nation. 
  For a few days, disturbances have been taking place in 
schools with the attendant threat to the freedom of citizens and 
to their property. I would like to appeal to all partners in 
the Malian educational sector -- school administrators, 
teachers, parents, and students -- to primarily resort to 
peaceful negotiations as the only way to safeguard this school 
year. I would like to take this opportunity to appeal to all 
sincere democrats and patriots to get involved in efforts to 
stop all adventurers who would like to plunge our country into 
anarchy. 
  We reiterate our unflinching determination to enforce the 
laws of the land, to protect citizens and their property, and to 
maintain law and order. Any instigation to revolt through false 
rumors or defamatory statements designed to incite hatred among 
Malians, at a time when our country rather needs to heal its 
wounds and restore national reconciliation, will be punished in 
accordance with the law. No great and lasting development can 
be achieved in disorder and insecurity. Our country has enough 
human and natural resources to overcome this crisis on condition 
that we all set to work in discipline. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-25148 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr027_e_94006" </HT>


