<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Reported TEC Stand on Detention Continues </TI></H3>
<H4>   IFP Wants Provision Abolished </H4>
<F P=102> MB0802174794 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 1100 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0802174794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Inkatha Freedom Party [IFP] has called for the 
scrapping of Section 29 of the Internal Security Act, which 
allows for detention without trial, and castigated the 
Transitional Executive Council for not abolishing the 
legislation. This followed the TEC's decision to retain 
provisionally Section 29 of the Internal Security Act. IFP 
spokesman Ed Tillet said in a statement in Durban that the TEC's 
decision made a mockery of the lengthy campaign fought by the 
ANC [African National Congress] and its allies to have the 
legislation removed from the statute books. 

</TEXT>

