<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Togo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Campaign Dates for 2d Round of Elections Announced </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1002183994 Dakar PANA in English 1705 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1002183994 </F>
<F P=104>  Dakar PANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lome, 10 Feb (PANA) -- Togo's second round 
parliamentary election campaigning is due to start on Friday [11 
February] and end on 18 February, it was officially announced 
Wednesday evening in Lome. In the first ballot, parties with 
links to President Gnassingbe Togolese People's Assembly [Rally] 
(RPT) won a total of 35 seats while 22 went to the opposition, 
according to provisional results published by the National 
Electoral Commission (CEN) in Lome. 
  Still at stake are 24 seats in 12 constituencies which are 
expected to be closely fought for by the two main opposition 
parties, the Action Committee for Renewal (CAR) of Yao 
Agboyibor, and the Togolese Union for Democracy (UTD) led by 
Edem Kodjo, a former minister and secretary general of the 
Organisation of African Unity (OAU). 
  A stiff competition is also expected between the RPT and the 
New Forces Coordination (CFN) of Prime Minister Joseph Kokou 
Koffigoh. A head-on collision between parties in the opposition 
grouping and pro-Eyadema parties is also inevitable in 11 
constituencies. 

</TEXT>

