<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Cote d'Ivoire </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition FPI Leader Gbagbo Breaks Silence </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1502122294 Abidjan Radio Cote d'Ivoire Chaine 
Nationale-Une Network in French 0700 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB1502122294 </F>
<F P=104>  Abidjan Radio Cote d'Ivoire Chaine 
Nationale-Une Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Laurent Gbagbo, secretary general of the Ivorian 
Popular Front [FPI], who had been silent since the death of 
President Houphouet-Boigny, broke his silence yesterday at a 
news conference at Assonvon Hotel, Yopougon district, Abidjan. 
Addressing the national and international media, the FPI leader 
touched on the current political, economic, and social problems 
facing our country. These include the devaluation of the CFA 
franc and its effects--whether good or bad--on us all; the 
political transitional period following the death of the first 
Ivorian president; some sections of our country's Constitution, 
especially the point concerning the succession issue; as well as 
other topics such as the election issue. Now let us listen to 
Laurent Gbagbo reaffirm his party's stand on Article 11 of the 
Constitution. 
  [Begin Gbagbo recording] The FPI is definitely against 
Article 11. It is against the current application of the 
article. It is against Article 11 today and tomorrow. It is 
also against the ideology on which Article 11 is based. 
Republican power is not given out in hereditary manner. Power 
should be won and regulations must be defined for the conquest 
of power. There is something fishy about the fact that the 
authorities, after the 1990 events, rushed to rearrange this 
Article 11, so we must stand against it. We opposed it, we are 
still opposed to it, and we will still be opposed to it in 
future. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

