<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Kenya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moi Ends KANU Cooperation With FORD-Kenya Opposition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA1102181094 Nairobi Kenya Broadcasting Corporation Network 
in English 1300 GMT 11 February 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1102181094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nairobi Kenya Broadcasting Corporation Network 
in English 1300 GMT 11 February 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] His Excellency President Daniel arap Moi has, 
with immediate effect, stopped any cooperation whatsoever 
between the ruling party, KANU [Kenya African National Union], 
and the FORD [Forum for the Restoration of Democracy]-Kenya 
party. And, at the same time, he warned of dire consequences 
for any KANU leader that will be seen to be cooperating with any 
officials from the FORD-Kenya party. 
  The president explained that when KANU accepted to cooperate 
with FORD-Kenya, it was because he knew the political policies 
of the late FORD-Kenya leader Jaramogi Oginga Odinga well, and 
Odinga too understood President Moi's policies. However, the 
president added that recent events and remarks by some 
FORD-Kenya officials have completely disqualified them from that 
cooperation. President Moi was speaking at the Kericho Show 
Ground when he officially opened this year's Kericho 
Agricultural Show. 
  The president further said that for the past two years he 
had 
been eagerly watching the outbusts and actions of some officials 
from FORD-Kenya and had come to the conclusion that those 
leaders had lost a sense of direction. He said KANU stood for 
peace and stability and cannot, therefore, enter into any 
cooperation with the party that excels in abuses. President 
Moi, who is also the president of the ruling party KANU, said he 
was definitely annoyed by the insults directed at him but 
restrained himself because of his great love for the children of 
this country. He, however, added that tolerance has a limit. 
[passage omitted]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

