<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Somalia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Red Cross Groups Evacuate After Grenade Attacks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1402161794 Paris AFP in English 1534 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1402161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nairobi, Feb 14 (AFP) -- Two Red Cross groups have 
withdrawn from Hiran region of Somalia, following hand grenade 
attacks on two non-governmental organisations' (NGOs) compounds 
in Beledweyne on February 9. 
  In a statement released here on Monday, the International 
Federation of the Red Cross and the German Red Cross 
(Federation/GRC) said that after the first attack, they had 
decided to pull out all NGO expatriates in the region, except 
the Federation's delegate and a respresentative of the 
International Medical Corps (IMC). 
  But the IMC and the Federation/GRC also pulled out the two 
on 
February 12 after another attack was aimed at the residence 
where they were staying. 
  Shortly before their departure on Saturday, the head of 
Federation Somalia delegation in Nairobi was informed by IMC 
through their Nairobi representative that the head of 
Federation/GRC sub-delegation in Beledweyne was also being held 
hostage and that his life was being threatened. 
  But he was released after frantic efforts by Federation/GRC 
and the Somali Red Crescent Society, and has now been flown to 
Nairobi. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

