<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Congo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Measures To Maintain Cease-Fire Announced </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1302224894 Brazzaville Radio Nationale Congolaise Network 
in French 1830 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB1302224894 </F>
<F P=104>  Brazzaville Radio Nationale Congolaise Network 
in French 1830 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] An intervention force is to be deployed in 
districts of Brazzaville where there have been socio-politicial 
disturbances. This measure, which forms a part of efforts to 
restore peace to our country, was initiated by the Parliamentary 
Standing Committee for Dialogue Between Pool and Niari 
Legislators. In a statement issued yesterday in Brazzaville, 
the committee warned all delinquents against attempting to 
disrupt the implementation of this measure. Let us listen to the 
statement: [read by announcer] 
  The executive of the Parliamentary Standing Committee for 
Dialogue Between Pool and Niari Legislators wishes to inform the 
Congolese people, especially those armed persons involved in 
recent clashes, that a cease-fire was decreed at midnight on 30 
January. This cease-fire is accompanied by a series of concrete 
measures that will contribute to restoring life to normalcy. 
Primary among these measures are: Fighters are to stop any 
further advancements; they are to withdraw with their arms; they 
are to lay down their arms and ammunition; and an intervention 
force is to be established that will be deployed on 14 February. 
In this regard, any armed person caught in the act of 
disrupting peace and order shall be punished in accordance with 
the law. 

</TEXT>

