<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Await Outcome of Investigation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1102180494 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 1600 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1102180494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The police have expressed the hope that its raid on 
the ANC's [African National Congress] Cape Town offices will not 
ruin its relations with the party. A police spokesman, Colonel 
Raymond Dowd, said the police met a delegation under the 
chairmanship of the Western Cape ANC Chairman Dr. Allan Boesak 
this afternoon to discuss the incident. Col. Dowd said that the 
actions of the Internal Stabiity Unit should not be condemned 
before the outcome of the investigation was known. 
  Earlier Law and Order Minister Hernus Kriel called in the 
help of the UN Observer Mission in South Africa in an attempt to 
protect the credibility of the police. Mr. Kriel said that he 
had asked the mission to make UN observers available on a 
24-hour basis, to accompany the police on any law enforcement 
duties involving entering the premises of any political party or 
organization. 
  The ANC has termed the raid on its Cape Town offices brutal 
and has called for the resignation of Mr. Kriel. The ANC 
demanded answers as to why the raid had taken place and what 
disciplinary steps would be taken against policemen responsible 
for alleged insults. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

