<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   South African Press Review for 15 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1502140294 </F>
<F P=103> MB1502140294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] 
<H6>  THE STAR </H6>
  Election Boycott Heightens Risk of Violence -- The Freedom 
Alliance (FA) boycott of the April election "has raised 
political temperatures and heightened the risk of increased 
violence," notes a page-14 editorial in Johannesburg THE STAR in 
English on 15 February. By not contesting the election, "the FA 
has put itself beyond the disciplinary sanction of the 
Independent Electoral Commission, a development which will 
complicate the task of controlling alliance zealots. Within 
hours of the IFP [Inkatha Freedom Party] decision to boycott the 
election, gunmen suspected of having IFP links attacked the 
Zevenfontein squatter camp, north of Johannesburg, killing four 
people and wounding nine more. The victims were reported to be 
ANC [African National Congress] supporters." 
<H6>  BUSINESS DAY </H6>
  Constraints of Single Ballot -- Johannesburg BUSINESS DAY in 
English on 15 February in a page-10 editorial believes the 
National Party (NP) and the ANC "may be inclined to withdraw 
their offer of a double ballot, with separate votes for national 
and regional government, now that the Freedom Alliance parties 
seem likely to boycott the election. But the constraints of a 
single ballot are plain. Only six of the 19 parties (including 
the major contestants) are contesting everything. Their 
supporters's single cross, in any region, will count for that 
party in Parliament and regional legislatures. People voting 
for any of the other 13 parties forfeit some choice." "One vote 
is supposed to count twice; in many cases it may count once, 
forcing voters to choose between a national say and a local one. 
Our new freedom has limits." 
<H6>  SOWETAN </H6>
  IFP, Freedom Alliance `Spoiling for a Fight' -- Johannesburg 
SOWETAN in English on 15 February in a page-8 editorial "would 
grant members of the IFP and the Freedom Alliance their right to 
boycott the elections -- just as we do Azapo [Azanian People's 
Organization] -- if they stopped their tactics of deliberately 
spoiling for a fight. The fact that the other parties taking 
part in the coming elections are doing everything to get these 
organisations into the elections exposes their refusal to go to 
the polls." 

</TEXT>

