<F P=103> MB1402194694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Words indistinct] because UN Special Representative 
Alioune Blondin Beye has again moved for an information 
blackout. This morning everyone was ready for the resumption of 
the peace talks, which should now discuss the role of the UN 
Angola Verification Mission-3, including a UN contingent of blue 
beret forces. 
  The UN special representative's team was the last to arrive, 
but it is already in Lusaka, and yesterday it met the leaders of 
the government and National Union for the Total Independence of 
Angola [UNITA] teams. 
  All this happens at a time when UNITA President Dr. Jonas 
Malheiro Savimbi, who is also Armed Forces for the Liberation of 
Angola [FALA] supreme commander, has expressed optimism and said 
he is ready for a political solution to the Angolan conflict. 
He expressed those views in interviews he granted to a 
Portuguese television station and to Portugal's O PUBLICO 
newspaper. UNITA said it favors a general cease-fire and asked 
Luanda to also make political concessions. 
  In those interviews Dr. Jonas Malheiro Savimbi rejected any 
possibility that there could be a military resolution to the 
Angolan conflict. 

