<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   Renamo Agrees To Withdraw From Salamanga </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1202172494 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
1600 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1202172494 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In a statement issued today, the Mozambique National 
Resistance [Renamo] has agreed to withdraw from Salamanga, 
Maputo Province, thus satisfying a demand from the Mozambican 
Government which claims it as an area under its control. For 
many months the government and Renamo have been arguing over 
allegations that Salamanga was occupied by Afonso Dhlakama's 
movement after the General Peace Accord was signed. 
  With this decision, Renamo will not only be carrying out the 
Supervision and Control Commission's [CSC] orders, but will also 
be withdrawing men and war materiel 10 or 30 km away from 
Salamanga. 
  Renamo said in its statement that it made this decision to 
avoid confrontations and to guarantee that peace was maintained 
and that war was not resumed. It said, however, that Salamanga 
must be viewed as a no-man's-land and has called on the 
government to observe such a status. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

