<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, Renamo To Demobilize Troops 1 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1202171894 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
1600 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1202171894 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The demobilization of troops from the government and 
the Mozambique National Resistance [Renamo] currently found in 
assembly areas will begin on 1 March. This decision was made 
today during a meeting of the Supervision and Control Commission 
[CSC] of the General Peace Accord. A total of 5 percent of 
troops from both sides will be demobilized in a first phase. 
  Until 1 March Finance Minister Eneas Comiche will create 
conditions to immediately pay the subsidies to the demobilized 
troops and to speed up solving the problems connected with their 
integration into civilian life. 
  Aldo Ajello, special representative of the UN secretary 
general in Mozambique, said although there is a considerable 
delay in the process, the demobilization process could continue 
until June. 
  During today's CSC meeting the government, Renamo and the UN 
Operations in Mozambique signed an agreement on criteria on the 
selection and training regulations of the special forces of the 
army. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

