<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows No Clear Majority in Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1002172294 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
1400 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1002172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] An opinion poll carried out by Gestinform reveals 
that if the multiparty elections were held in January this year, 
there would be no absolute majorities both in presidential and 
legislative elections. In the opinion poll, in which 4,000 
people were interviewed throughout the country, Joaquim 
Chissano, Mozambique Liberation Front [Frelimo] presidential 
candidate, has 45.4 percent of the votes, followed by Mozambique 
National Resistance's [Renamo] Afonso Dhlakama with 32.4 
percent. Dr. Domingos Arouca, leader of the Mozambique United 
Front has 3.3 percent of the votes, followed by Mozambican 
Nationalist Movement's [Monamo] Maximo Dias with 2.4 percent. 
  President of the Republic Joaquim Chissano obtained the most 
votes in Gaza Province, his original home area, where he 
received 60 percent of the votes, and Inhambane where he 
received 61 percent. 
  The Renamo presidential candidate obtained the best results 
-- 49.3 percent -- in Sofala Province where Renamo's general 
headquarters is found. 
  Regarding legislative elections, Frelimo obtained 38.1 
percent of the votes and Renamo 34.2 percent. Monamo received 
4.1 percent, Fumo 3.6 percent, the National Convention Party 2.8 
percent, while the remaining parties received 4.2 percent 
combined. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

