<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Zimbabwe </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Offer Said Not Enough To Deploy Troops in Liberia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0902205394 Gaborone Radio Botswana Network in English 1910 
GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0902205394 </F>
<F P=104>  Gaborone Radio Botswana Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zimbabwe says it will not send troops to join 
peacekeeping forces in Liberia because the United Nations is not 
offering enough money to cover the operation. The country's 
defense minister, Mr. Moven Mahachi, said today that Zimbabwe 
has already lined up a battalion of soldiers for duty in Liberia 
at the request of the United Nations but they will not be 
deployed unless more money is made available. Zimbabwe has 
troops with UN forces in Somalia and Mr. Mahachi said his 
government had learned from experience that the money available 
for the Liberian exercise was just not enough. 
  He said America had put up 31 million dollars for 
Zimbabwean, 
Ugandan, and Tanzanian troops due to go to Liberia and argued 
that the United Nations should approach other countries for more 
funds. Ugandan and Tanzanian troops have already been sent to 
join a Nigerian-led peace-keeping force in Liberia under the 
terms of an accord signed between rival Liberian factions in 
July last year, to put an end to a brutal civil war that began 
in December 1989. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

