<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Election Unlikely To Be Postponed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1502203894 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in Afrikaans 
1600 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1502203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Afrikaans </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] State President F.W. de Klerk says he does not 
see the election being postponed although this could 
theoretically be possible. Mr. de Klerk was speaking at a news 
conference in Pretoria a short while ago. Johan Claasen reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Claasen] According to Mr. de Klerk the 
refusal by certain political groups to participate in the 
elections could theoretically lead to a postponement. He does 
believe, however, that support for an election on the 27 April 
is sufficient to assure that it will take place. He called on 
all parties to register for the elections as soon as possible. 
He said that even though time is extremely limited there is 
still room for negotiation. 
  [De Klerk, in English] Practicality suggests that we are now 
talking merely about reaching agreements within a few days, at 
the most a week, and calling Parliament together rather soon. 
  [Claasen] Referring to the demands of King Goodwill 
Zwelithini, Mr. de Klerk says there will be definite proposals 
on the table on Thursday, which hopefully, will be acceptable to 
the king. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

