<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   Establishment of Transitional Government Postponed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1502143294 Brussels LA LIBRE BELGIQUE in French 15 Feb 94 
p 5 </F>

<F P=103> BR1502143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels LA LIBRE BELGIQUE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Marie-France Cros: "An `Incomprehensible' </F>
Blockage: The United Nations Clashes With Presidential 
Supporters Who Want Amnesty"] 
  [Text] Once again, the establishment of the transitional 
government and assembly, as provided for in the peace agreement 
between the Rwandan Government and rebel forces that was 
concluded in August 1993, has been postponed. Nonetheless, last 
Thursday, UN Envoy Jacques Booh Booh had reached a consensus 
between all the parties concerned to proceed Monday with the 
establishment of these transitional institutions, even if the 
two wings of the Liberal Party [PL] could not agree on who would 
represent them within these institutions. Originally, the 
transitional institutions should have become operational on 31 
December 1993. 
<H5>  Empty Seats </H5>
  On Sunday, the former single party, the National Republican 
Movement for Democracy and Development [MRND] did not turn up at 
the meeting planned by MINUAR (the UN Mission in Rwanda -- LA 
LIBRE BELGIQUE editor's note), nor was the Hutu branch of the 
PL, led by Justin Mugenzi, who has brought off a spectacular 
reconciliation with both President Habyarimana and the MRND in 
recent months. Consequently, the meeting had to be postponed 
and, as a result, the institutions could not be set up on 
Monday, as planned. "We do not understand this blockage," said 
MINUAR spokesman Gueye. 
  Gueye added that the MRND "had nevertheless wanted to 
present 
a code of conduct for the parties at the meeting, stating that 
they undertake to vote in favor of a general amnesty, and ensure 
the neutrality of the administration" during the transitional 
period leading up to the elections scheduled to be held around 
20 months from now. 

</TEXT>

