<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Observers Meet With UNITA, Government Delegations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1502194494 Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro in 
Portuguese 1900 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1502194494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Angolan peace talks in Lusaka, the capital of 
Zambia, are moving slowly but also progressing. Today the 
United Nations and the troika of observers presented a new 
document on national reconciliation to the sides. The contents 
of the document are not known, but it is known that it is the 
result of points of view presented by the National Union for the 
Total Independence of Angola [UNITA] and the government. 
  The two sides held meetings with the mediators this morning 
and once again this afternoon. Although no diplomat has made 
statements to the press, the countenance of the negotiators was 
described as encouraging. Observers have said the issue of 
national reconciliation in Angola, a country at war for more 
than 30 years, is not an ease issue to deal with. However, UN 
Special Representative Alioune Blondin Beye still believes in a 
solution for this delicate point. UNITA also believes in this 
and hopes that Luanda, which has not yet made concessions, may 
do so to achieve peace and democracy in Angola. Thus, the ball 
is on the side of the Popular Movement for the Liberation of 
Angola-Labor Party. 

</TEXT>

