<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Troops Reportedly Recapture Northern Towns </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1502183794 Johannesburg Channel Africa Radio in English 
1610 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1502183794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Channel Africa Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Government troops in Angola are said to have won 
back three towns in the country's northern province of Bengo. 
However the government newspaper, JORNAL DE ANGOLA, says 
government troops are under heavy guerrilla pressure in Caxito, 
some 50 km from the capital, Luanda. The paper said today that 
the northerly towns of Nnambuangongo, Ucua, and Ambriz fell to 
the army after fierce battles with UNITA [National Union for the 
Total Independence of Angola] rebels which began in mid-January, 
but it gave no casualty figures. 
  Independent sources in Luanda said there was still heavy 
fighting in the border regions between Bengo, more than half of 
which is in government hands, and Uige Province, wholly held by 
UNITA. 
  In the southernmost province of Huila, where army-rebel 
clashes have broken out, a military spokesman in the chief town, 
Lubango, said troops had recaptured the iron mining town of 
Jamba, after a five-day fight to dislodge UNITA units, which 
overran Jamba on 3 February. 

</TEXT>

