<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Burkina Faso </F>
<H3> <TI>   Timetable Under Discussion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1502165694 Ouagadougou Radiodiffusion Nationale du Burkina 
Radio in French 1300 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB1502165694 </F>
<F P=104>  Ouagadougou Radiodiffusion Nationale du Burkina 
Radio </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The preparations for negotiations are currently in 
place at Ouagadougou, where delegations of the Niger Government 
and the Tuareg opposition have arrived for a technical meeting 
to fix a timetable for negotiations to end the Tuareg conflict 
in Niger. The dispute has been going on for nearly three years 
now. Yesterday evening, the head of state received the two 
delegations separately. Each audience lasted about one hour. 
Today, the Burkinabe envoys are pursuing their discussions with 
the two delegations in order to establish a working program 
likely to bring everyone around the same table. Radio Burkina 
contacted the leaders of the two delegations who showed optimism 
about the effective takeoff of these trilateral consultations. 
  Kriska, of the Coordination of Armed Resistance, which 
includes all the Tuareg movements, says this slowdown is caused 
by technical problems. A few modifications need to be made, 
however that these are not necessarily preconditions. As for 
the head of the government delegation, Abdourahamane Hama, who 
is Niger's foreign affairs and cooperation minister, the 
consultations remain informal because this enables them to 
proceed prudently. Both claim that a joint meeting is probable 
either this evening or tomorrow morning. 

</TEXT>

