<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Warring Factions Begin `Last Chance' Talks Session </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1602114594 Paris AFP in English 1523 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1602114594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Monrovia, l5 Feb (AFP) -- Liberia's rival factions 
began fresh talks here on Tuesday [15 February] to try to 
overcome political and military problems which have for months 
blocked implementation of last year's peace agreement. The main 
sticking points are disarmament of the various armed groups and 
the setting up of transitional institutions ahead of elections 
supposed to be staged this month. 
  U.N. special envoy Trevor Gordon Somers is chairing the 
latest closed-doors parley. A marathon six-week session which 
opened in December made no progress. Delegates said they 
regarded the new discussions as a "last chance" to sort out 
their differences. 
  The interim government is at loggerheads with the main rebel 
movement the Patriotic Front and its rival United Liberation 
Movement, which are both insisting on getting the key ministries 
of foreign affairs, defence, justice and finance. 
  The new round of talks is being attended by General John 
Inienger, commander of the military monitoring force of some 
l9,000 troops stationed in Liberia by the 16-nation Economic 
Community of West African States since August 1990. 

</TEXT>

