<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   ANC Condemns Zulu King's Hints About Secession </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1502153994 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1430 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1502153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Durban Feb 15 SAPA -- The African National Congress 
[ANC] on Tuesday [15 February] condemned Monday's hints of 
secession by Zulu King Goodwill Zwelithini, saying his demands 
for an autonomous Zulu state came directly from the Inkatha 
Freedom Party [IFP]. ANC Southern Natal Regional Secretary Sbu 
Ndebele said Monday was "a sad day for the Zulu-speaking people 
of South Africa", because it saw the Zulu monarch taking a 
"radical decision" which had not been tested by popular vote. 
  He said King Zwelithini had singled out IFP President 
Mangosuthu Buthelezi as "God's gift to the Zulu people", which 
was an "inconceivable position" since royalty was not supposed 
to be politically aligned. "The majority of the king's subjects 
do not belong to the IFP. The Zulu nation is not a single, 
monolithic bloc united in its support for a partisan political 
policy," he said. 
  The ANC was currently drafting its own proposals for the 
Natal provincial constitution and the monarchy would "take pride 
of place" in that constitution. 
  The ANC charged that Mr Buthelezi had used the king for 
party 
political purposes, adding that the ANC would entrench the 
king's independence in a provincial constitution "so that his 
place doesn't depend on the whim of the governing party and the 
king will be enabled to play a unifying role to all the people". 
  On Monday King Zwelithini told State President F W de Klerk 
at a meeting in Durban that acceptance of the Zulu nation, as it 
existed in the 1800s, was not negotiable. He said the Zulu 
nation was a sovereign one and could not be overruled by the 
interim constitution. Mr de Klerk said he did not regard the 
king's claims as secession and said the government would 
officially respond to them on Thursday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

