<F P=101> Gabon </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Leader Calls For Civil Disobedience Meaures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1602175694 Paris AFP in French 1844 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1602175694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Libreville, 15 Feb (AFP) -- Father Paul Mba 
Abessole, Gabon's main opposition leader, today called on his 
followers to "refuse to pay" local taxes and "disobey all 
government directives." 
  In a statement to the press, Father Mba Abessole, who placed 
second in the 5 December presidential elections and contested 
President Omar Bongo's reelection, also reaffirmed the 
determination of his party, the National Lumberjacks Rally, not 
"to participate in any other local or national election" 
organized by the government, since the ballot paper has no value 
at present in Gabon." 
  In this regard, the Lumberjacks leader sees yesterday's 
announcement, that local elections slated for March 27 have been 
postponed to 28 August, as a "retreat imposed" by the 
government. Father Mba Abessole also invited opposition members 
who have rallied round him in the Convention of the Forces of 
Change "to reject any form of participation in a government of 
national union or large consensus," which President Bongo has 
called for several times since his reelection. Those who "join 
such a government would by that very fact be excluded from our 
ranks," he warned. 

</TEXT>

