<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Gabon </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unions Maintain Strike; Action Said Unsuccessful </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1602141694 Libreville Africa No. 1 in French 0730 GMT 16 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB1602141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Libreville Africa No. 1 </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Gabonese Trade Union Confederation [COSYGA] 
has expressed its determination to go ahead with its planned 
three-day general strike starting today to press for concrete 
measures to cope with the soaring prices caused by the 
devaluation of the CFA franc. The workers are also pressing for 
an 80-percent wage increase. Prime Minister Oye-Mba held talks 
with union leaders on 14 January and told them that his 
government was examining further measures designed to alleviate 
the adverse effects of the devaluation through the subsidization 
of certain basic commodities. [passage omitted] 
  [In a related report at 1215 GMT on 16 February 1994, 
Libreville Radio adds: "The 72-hour strike called by COSYGA 
seems to have received little support. The movement was not 
very much observed and Libreville residents in particular are 
quietly going about their normal business, both in the public 
and private sectors." 
  [Libreville Radio says that the personnel officer for the 
Libreville municipal council said the following: "Reports 
reaching me from the region say that the strike has only been 
partially observed. I am happy to report that a large number of 
our employees have come to work."] 

</TEXT>

