<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks on National Reconciliation Continue in Lusaka </TI></H3>
<H4>   UNITA Accused of Inflexibility </H4>
<F P=102> MB1602202594 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1602202594 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Pedro Manuel in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] Good evening. The negotiators are holding lengthy 
talks in a bid to find common ground concerning the general 
principles for national reconciliation. At this stage, the 
mediators virtually have no idea of how to approach the third 
version of the general principles because the National Union for 
the Total Independence of Angola [UNITA] continues to say no to 
discussing legal issues. 
  After this afternoon's session, sources reported that there 
were many areas of agreement. There are no agreements yet 
concerning general national reconciliation principles because 
UNITA does not want to discuss the legal side of the dossier. 
Both the government and the mediators believe that the dossier 
should be discussed both along political and legal lines. 
  The mediators and the observers have undertaken to work with 
the UNITA team this evening in a bid to settle the problem. 
They will attempt to persuade UNITA to accept discussions that 
can always fall back on the country's existing legal framework. 
  A source said that if the mediators manage to get UNITA to 
agree to that, perhaps there might be an agreement on the 
general principles of national reconciliation by tomorrow. That 
source noted, that the issue of the general national 
reconciliation principle is just the first part of the dossier. 
In a clear reference to the issue of the ministerial portfolios 
and specific national reconciliation principles, that source 
said that heated talks are on the way. They will try to do away 
with possible loopholes to avoid any complications when those 
principles are implemented. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

