<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks on National Reconciliation Continue in Lusaka </TI></H3>
<H4>   Progress Termd `Piecemeal' </H4>
<F P=102> MB1702113794 Luanda TPA Television Network in Portuguese 
1930 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1702113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda TPA Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Joao Ligio in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] Progress at the Lusaka peace talks is piecemeal and 
with too many breaks. The mediator and the troika of observers 
succeeded in having the two sides agreeing to four of the five 
[as heard] points of the second document under discussion. The 
four points are: general principles on political tolerance, 
nondiscriminatory coexistence of all ethnic groups, the 
involvement of all Angolans in the process of national 
reconciliation regardless of their political, ethnic, and 
religious origin, and the adoption by the news media of a 
behavior that conforms with patriotism and a unitary state. 
  This afternoon's plenary session was scheduled to deal with 
the only outstanding issue, but it was replaced by separate 
consultations because the National Union for the Total 
Independence of Angola introduced a proposal that the government 
delegation rejected outright. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

