<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Zimbabwe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thousands of Telecommunications Workers Go on Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1602131494 Johannesburg Channel Africa Radio in English 
1100 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1602131494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Channel Africa Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Thousands of workers at Zimbabwe's state run Posts 
and Telecommunications Corporation have begun an indefinite 
strike to press for higher wages. The union leader said the 
10,500 workers wanted a 12.5 percent increase which a labor 
relations tribunal has said must be dated back to July 1992. 
Many services were not available because of today's strike but 
senior staff were maintaining essential operations. The 
corporation said the strike was illegal and the workers risked 
losing their jobs. The corporation has appealed to the Supreme 
Court against the ruling by the labor relations tribunal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

