<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Klerk Responds to Concessions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1702071194 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2204 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1702071194 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by State President F.W. de Klerk on the SAPA PR </F>
wire service on 16 February] 
  [Text] The government and the National Party [NP] have, 
over the past weeks, done everything in their power to make an 
inclusive negotiated settlement possible. Various proposals and 
counter-proposals were tabled in the process. This led to the 
government's negotiating team making a proposal on 2 February 
this year which, in our opinion, could resolve the deadlock. 
  The ANC [African National Congress] has now dropped its 
opposition to important aspects of this proposal and we believe 
that this offers the opportunity to all parties, including the 
Freedom Alliance [FA] parties, to participate in the elections. 
In particular, the proposal addresses two matters which were of 
key importance to the parties of the Freedom Alliance, namely a 
constitutional principle which makes provision for 
self-determination and a related mechanism which gives further 
attention to the idea of a "volkstaat" [Afrikaner homeland] and 
a constitutional principle which provides that the powers and 
capabilities of the provinces will in essence be maintained. 
All the other matters are, however, also of crucial importance. 
  The road to peaceful participation in the election is, in 
our 
opinion, now open to all parties and the government expresses 
its hope that the Freedom Alliance will now place the interests 
of South Africa and of its own voters first. 

</TEXT>

